{"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/Quick-start","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"metadata":{"title":"Quick start","modules":[{"name":"SwiftCrossUI"}],"role":"article","roleHeading":"Article"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Creating a cross-platform SwiftCrossUI app with Swift Bundler."}],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Overview","anchor":"Overview"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"This quick start guide uses ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/stackotter\/swift-bundler","isActive":true},{"text":". Although not strictly required, it simplifies many aspects of cross-platform distribution and provides a platform-agnostic configuration format for specifying things such as app icons and custom URL schemes.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"aside","style":"note","name":"Note","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If you’re new to Swift, we recommend starting with ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/Setting-up-a-development-environment","type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Installing Swift Bundler","anchor":"Installing-Swift-Bundler"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Follow "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/stackotter\/swift-bundler?tab=readme-ov-file#installation-","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":". "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"mint"},{"type":"text","text":" is the preferred installation method on macOS and Linux as of the last update to this quick start guide."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Installing system dependencies","anchor":"Installing-system-dependencies"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Each backend has different requirements. In this guide we’ll use "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documen